<DocsLayout
  title="Extensibility"
  eyebrow="Philosophy"
  description="gode is designed to be everyone's editor — moldable at every layer."
  prev={{ href: "/docs/architecture/", title: "godex harness" }}
  next={{ href: "/docs/event-bus/", title: "Event bus & journal" }}
>
  <p>
    A foundational goal of gode is for it to be <strong>everyone's editor</strong>. That
    only works if it is extensible and moldable at every layer — from the harness internals
    a research lab forks, all the way out to the addon a single user drops in.
  </p>

  <p>
    Extensibility is not a feature bolted on top. It shapes the architecture: the event bus
    is a public seam, the tool registry is uniform across built-ins and external tools, and
    transports are pluggable. Whatever you want to build, there is a place to plug it in
    without forking the world.
  </p>

  <h2>Layers of extensibility</h2>

  <h3>1. Fork the harness</h3>
  <p>
    <code>godex</code> is a Go package. ML labs and tooling teams that need deep changes
    can fork it: swap the runner, add new event types, replace the journal format, wire in
    custom telemetry. Because every state transition flows through a typed bus, modifying
    one part of the system rarely cascades into the rest.
  </p>
  <p>
    This is the right layer for research: train a coding agent against a custom reward
    signal, capture trajectories from the journal, replay them deterministically, swap the
    provider for a local model.
  </p>

  <h3>2. Embed the CLI</h3>
  <p>
    <code>gode</code> is a single static binary. It runs in CI, in cron jobs, inside other
    binaries, behind webhooks — anywhere you can shell out. Provider, workspace, data
    directory, MCP servers, and approval policy are all flags or environment.
  </p>
  <pre><code>gode acp --provider mock --auto-approve
gode app-server --listen ws://127.0.0.1:0
make ask PROMPT="summarize this repo"</code></pre>

  <h3>3. MCP — language-agnostic tools</h3>
  <p>
    Model Context Protocol servers are the right answer when you want to extend the agent's
    capabilities without writing Go and without rebuilding gode. Spawn a process, expose
    tools, attach it to a session. gode is a strong reference implementation: tools are
    surfaced as <code>mcp.&lt;server&gt;.&lt;tool&gt;</code> in the same registry as
    built-ins, with the same permissions surface and the same event lifecycle.
  </p>

  <h3>4. Skills</h3>
  <p>
    Skills are reusable, declarative capabilities the agent can invoke — the layer above
    raw tools. gode treats skills as first-class: they are discoverable, manageable from
    the TUI, and reuse the same tool registry underneath. They are how you bundle "the way
    we do X here" into something the agent can pick up across sessions.
  </p>

  <h3>5. Transports and clients</h3>
  <p>
    The TUI, ACP, and app-server all sit on top of the same godex core. If your editor or
    agent client speaks ACP, gode is already an agent for it. If it speaks the Codex
    app-server style, gode is already a server for it. Adding a third transport is a
    matter of subscribing to the bus and translating events to your wire format.
  </p>

  <h3>6. Compiled Go addons (planned)</h3>
  <p>
    For users who want native-speed extensions without forking the harness, gode is
    planned to support <strong>compiled Go addons</strong>. The model: drop in a Go module
    that registers tools, event subscribers, or transport adapters, and have it loaded at
    startup with no interpreter, no IPC overhead, and no shimming. Built-in performance
    for third-party code.
  </p>

  <div class="callout">
    <strong>Why compiled addons over scripting?</strong> Coding agents are latency-sensitive
    systems. Every tool call, every event delivery, every diff applied is on the hot path.
    A compiled addon model keeps third-party extensions on the same performance footing as
    everything else in the binary.
  </div>

  <h2>Pick your layer</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Research labs</strong> → fork the harness. You want maximum control and the journal as ground truth.</li>
    <li><strong>Platform teams</strong> → embed the CLI. You want repeatable, headless agent runs in your existing pipelines.</li>
    <li><strong>Tool authors</strong> → ship an MCP server. Language-agnostic, isolated, easy to distribute.</li>
    <li><strong>Workflow authors</strong> → publish a skill. Capture how your team works without writing code.</li>
    <li><strong>Editor / client builders</strong> → speak ACP or the app-server protocol. The agent core is yours.</li>
    <li><strong>Performance-critical extenders</strong> → wait for compiled Go addons, or fork today.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>The constant</h2>
  <p>
    Across every layer, the contract is the same: typed events on a shared bus, tools
    behind a uniform registry, sessions as journaled JSONL. Extend any layer and the rest
    of the system keeps working — that is what "moldable" means in practice.
  </p>
